04450nam a22006495i 9780822373285DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20172017ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016037764  a97808223732857 a10.1515/97808223732852doi  a(DE-B1597)554153  a(OCoLC)1152990061  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC10aHD9672.I42 4aHD9672.I42 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a338.8/87161512231 aSunder Rajan, Kaushik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPharmocracy :bValue, Politics, and Knowledge in Global Biomedicine /cKaushik Sunder Rajan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b1 illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExperimental futures : technological lives, scientific arts, anthropological voices : 2000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Value, Politics, and Knowledge in the Pharmocracy -- tChapter One. Speculative Values: Pharmaceutical Crisis and Financialized Capital -- tChapter Two. Bioethical Values: HPV Vaccines, Public Scandal, and Experimental Subjectivity -- tChapter Three. Constitutional Values: The Trials of Gleevec and Judicialized Politics -- tChapter Four. Philanthropic Values: Corporate Social Responsibility and Monopoly in the Pharmocracy -- tChapter Five. Postcolonial Values: Nationalist Industries in Pharmaceutical Empire -- tConclusion. Constitutions of Health, Responsibility, and Democracy -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContinuing his pioneering theoretical explorations into the relationships among biosciences, the market, and political economy, Kaushik Sunder Rajan introduces the concept of pharmocracy to explain the structure and operation of the global hegemony of the multinational pharmaceutical industry. He reveals pharmocracy's logic in two case studies from contemporary India: the controversial introduction of an HPV vaccine in 2010, and the Indian Patent Office's denial of a patent for an anticancer drug in 2006 and ensuing legal battles. In each instance health was appropriated by capital and transformed from an embodied state of well-being into an abstract category made subject to capital's interests. These cases demonstrate the precarious situation in which pharmocracy places democracy, as India's accommodation of global pharmaceutical regulatory frameworks pits the interests of its citizens against those of international capital. Sunder Rajan's insights into this dynamic make clear the high stakes of pharmocracy's intersection with health, politics, and democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPapillomaviruses - Vaccination - India - Case studies. 0aPapillomavirusesxVaccinationzIndiavCase studies. 0aPapillomavirusesxVaccinationzIndiaxCase studies. 0aPapillomavirusesxVaccinationzIndia. 0aPharmaceutical industryxEconomic aspects. 0aPharmaceutical industryxManagement. 0aPharmaceutical industryzIndia. 0aPolitics, Practical. 0aSocial values. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106963490 cprintz978082236313240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373285?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822373285/original  a978-3-11-069634-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles